public int getFirstItemNotObscuredByHeader() {
    // Assumes access to the RecyclerView (mRecyclerView), adapter (mAdapter),
    // and a helper: Rect getHeaderBounds(int position)
    int childCount = mRecyclerView.getChildCount();
    for (int i = 0; i < childCount; i++) {
        View child = mRecyclerView.getChildAt(i);
        int position = mRecyclerView.getChildAdapterPosition(child);
        if (position == RecyclerView.NO_POSITION) continue;

        Rect headerBounds = getHeaderBounds(position); // may return null if no header
        int headerBottom = (headerBounds != null) ? headerBounds.bottom : Integer.MIN_VALUE;

        // If the child's top is at or below the header's bottom, it's not obscured
        if (child.getTop() >= headerBottom) {
            return position;
        }
        // otherwise, this item is obscured by the header; continue checking
    }
    return RecyclerView.NO_POSITION;
}

Notes:
- If there is no header currently obscuring items (headerBottom effectively very small or negative), the first visible item will typically be returned.
- getHeaderBounds(int position) is used conceptually based on the provided Rect getHeaderBounds capability.
